[[File:Sai_SWLEG31.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Cade Skywalker utilizing ''sai'' while dueling Darth Stryfe.]]

In [[Lightsaber combat/Legends|lightsaber combat]], '''''sai''''' was a jump used by [[Jedi/Legends|Jedi]] and other [[The Force/Legends|Force-users]] to evade an attack directed at the legs.

==Methodology and Examples==
[[File:Full_of_Surprises.jpg|thumb|left|180px|Luke Skywalker performing the ''sai'' during his duel with Darth Vader]]

While the primary purpose of the ''sai'' was to simply overleap an attack, it could also be applied tactically, such as facilitating retreat or counter-attack. What action the duelist performed depended on the way he jumped, the Force being the main backbone of the [[Wikipedia:strength|strength]], [[Wikipedia:height|height]], and [[Wikipedia:speed|speed]] at which the jump was executed.<ref name="Fightsaber">{{InsiderCite|62|Fightsaber: Jedi Lightsaber Combat}}</ref>

For counter-attacking, the ''sai'' provided several options. The most common was to use the fall as the fulcrum for an overhand blow, a maneuver demonstrated by [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Darth Vader]] during his duel with [[Roan Shryne]].<ref name="TRODV">''[[Dark Lord: The Rise of Darth Vader]]''</ref> Another method of countering involved simply using the height of the jump to attack from above, an example being [[Kit Fisto/Legends|Kit Fisto's]] midair cartwheeling during [[Mission to Grievous's castle/Legends|his duel]] with [[Grievous/Legends|Grievous]], allowing him to cut at the cyborg.<ref name="Lair of Grievous">{{TCW|Lair of Grievous}}</ref> [[Dooku/Legends|Dooku]] demonstrated a more passive variation of this method during his bout with [[Obi-Wan Kenobi/Legends|Obi-Wan Kenobi]], flourishing his blade as he leapt to drive back Kenobi.<ref name="AOTC">{{Film|II}}</ref>

The ''sai'' has also been applied in more tactical functions, for retreating or outflanking opponents. A technique demonstrated by [[Luke Skywalker/Legends|Luke Skywalker]] during his duel with Darth Vader involved leaping above the opponent and attacking from behind.<ref name="TESB">{{Film|V}}</ref> This method became associated with the [[Form IV/Legends|Ataru combat form]]. However, it was not without risk, as the opponent could simply stab upward while the duelist was above them.<ref name="ROTSn">[[Star Wars: Revenge of the Sith (novelization)|''Star Wars'': Episode III ''Revenge of the Sith'' novelization]]</ref> The ''sai'' has also been applied to allow for retreat, the duelist simply leaping away when they overleapt the attack, as shown by Luke Skywalker's retreat from Vader during [[Battle of Endor/Legends#Demise of the Sith|their rematch]], leaping onto an overhead gantry.<ref name="ROTJ">{{Film|VI}}</ref>

Even a non Force-sensitive could use sai such as [[Durge/Legends|Durge]] against [[Anakin Skywalker/Legends|Anakin Skywalker]] in their last fight and [[Jango Fett/Legends|Jango Fett]] on [[Galidraan/Legends|Galidraan]] against [[Myles]]' [[Unidentified Jedi (Myles' killer)|killer]].

